WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.860
So that being said, with CAR-T, typically we have major side effects, which are cytokine release

00:00:06.860 --> 00:00:12.920
and neurotoxicity, which initially resulted in prolonged hospitalizations, high utilization of

00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:22.000
healthcare, and quite expensive. So if you think back to the timeline of CAR-T, in 2017, the first

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:28.360
commercial CAR-T was approved. In January of 2018, we began our outpatient CAR-T practice.

00:00:29.460 --> 00:00:37.820
In March of 2020, we started our remote patient monitoring program. And then in about three and

00:00:37.820 --> 00:00:42.040
a half years ago, we started a community paramedic program, which I will describe further.

00:00:42.860 --> 00:00:48.060
Let's get through this. So the settings. So if you look at the schematic on the right,

00:00:48.060 --> 00:00:51.740
number one is the Mayo Clinic. That is an eight to five clinic,

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.380
we see our consults, we see our day 30 returns. Number two, which is just above that,

00:00:57.860 --> 00:01:01.580
is in the front of the hospital. It's the hospital-based outpatient.

00:01:02.720 --> 00:01:07.100
That is where patients will come in daily. It is connected to the Mayo Clinic by

00:01:07.100 --> 00:01:11.760
skyways and a subway. And then number three is where inpatient service is.

00:01:13.340 --> 00:01:18.600
Number four represents the Gift of Life transplant house, which is about a half a mile

00:01:18.600 --> 00:01:21.460
from the hospital and where most patients stay.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:29.420
So again, laying the setting. Our remote patient monitoring system is a kit that includes a tablet.

00:01:29.980 --> 00:01:37.820
It has a sphingomanometer that Bluetooths the data to the tablet. It's got a pulse ox,

00:01:37.820 --> 00:01:44.380
a digital Bluetooth scale, and a thermometer. And then the community paramedic program. This

00:01:44.380 --> 00:01:50.580
was established usually for primary and preventive care. But for CAR-T patients, we utilize it for

00:01:50.580 --> 00:01:57.460
later time points for blood draws, to assess for transfusion needs, to do medical assessments.

00:01:58.260 --> 00:02:02.260
They are under the guidance of a RIMS-certified hematology provider.

00:02:02.820 --> 00:02:08.260
So what about the outpatient CAR-T practice? So we base this on our multiple myeloma model.

00:02:08.980 --> 00:02:13.700
We've done over 10,000 transplants over the history of our transplant program.

00:02:13.700 --> 00:02:20.540
But we looked at our day 100 all-cause mortality, and it was only 0.3 percent utilizing an outpatient

00:02:20.540 --> 00:02:25.900
setting. So we thought we could do this with CAR-T. So the initial CAR-T consult is done in

00:02:25.900 --> 00:02:31.180
the Mayo Clinic all the way up until lymphodepleting chemo, when the patient's transferred to the

00:02:31.180 --> 00:02:37.740
hospital-based outpatient. And that goes through day 30. And then at day 30 onwards, it goes back

00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:44.860
to the outpatient and Mayo Clinic. The cartoon on the right sort of shows the flow where,

00:02:44.860 --> 00:02:50.220
you know, patients get their lymphodepleting chemo. They start their remote monitoring, and they're

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:56.380
done. And then it really is a flow back and forth with the hospital. The inpatient consultant

00:02:56.380 --> 00:03:02.700
actually oversees the outpatient unit. We know that there are certain things that increase risk

00:03:02.700 --> 00:03:08.380
for early hospitalization, including the need for bridging therapy, elevated LDH, et cetera.

00:03:10.220 --> 00:03:15.900
So we looked at the first 120 patients. Eighty-five percent were infused as an outpatient.

00:03:16.620 --> 00:03:19.020
About a fifth of those were never hospitalized.

00:03:19.980 --> 00:03:26.460
Actually, a minor percentage was infused as an inpatient. Looking at the utilization of CARE,

00:03:26.460 --> 00:03:33.980
I'll just point out the top line, and it's going against time, is where patients came

00:03:33.980 --> 00:03:40.620
into the outpatient unit requiring nothing. No infusions, no electrolytes. Sorry.

00:03:42.540 --> 00:03:49.500
Running out of time. So what about the remote patient monitoring? That, as I described, it's a

00:03:49.740 --> 00:03:58.300
remote tablet, which uploads information. It is then transmitted to a remote nurse who is

00:03:58.300 --> 00:04:05.180
monitoring the data. This is reimbursable. Medicare, Medicaid in 34 states will reimburse for

00:04:05.180 --> 00:04:11.100
this. So in the cartoon on the right, the patient takes their vitals on number one.

00:04:11.740 --> 00:04:16.140
It's uploaded to the cloud. And then in number three, it is evaluated

00:04:16.140 --> 00:04:19.500
through an algorithm to determine if the patient needs to be seen

00:04:19.500 --> 00:04:23.180
or not. So this is how it works. I'll show you a little bit of a picture of what this looks like.

